SIMPLE: gradatory
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gradatory
<hw>Grad"a*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Grade</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Proceeding step by step, or by
gradations; gradual.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Could we have seen [Macbeth's] crimes darkening on their progress
. . . could this <qex>gradatory</qex> apostasy have been shown us.</q>
<rj><qau>A. Seward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Suitable for walking; -- said of
the limbs of an animal when adapted for walking on land.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gradatory</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gradatory
<hw>Grad"a*to*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LL.
<ets>gradatarium</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A series of steps
from a cloister into a church.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grade</ent>⟦br⟧
